        "confidence": "low"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "u003",
      "speaker": "dev-navarro",
      "type": "speech",
      "text": "I don\u2019t think the show is confused about branching; I think it\u2019s confused about how much it wants to reassure you that the universe is *legible*. The numbers feel deterministic because, emotionally, they\u2019re there to be a stress-test that says \u201cyou will be accountable,\u201d not \u201cyou will be surprised.\u201d So on your island authority vs Dharma vs Jacob/Smokey triangle\u2014what scene makes you feel like the Numbers are being used as *instruction*, versus being used as *evidence*?",
      "delivery": {
        "emotion": "warm, skeptical",
        "pace": "slightly_slow",
        "volume": "normal",
        "emphasis": [
          "legible-universe",
          "accountability-not-surprise",
          "instruction-vs-evidence"
        ],
        "notes": "Keep it psychological\u2014don\u2019t litigate canon too hard yet; force Mara to pick an example."
      },
      "anchor": {
        "phrase": "deterministic",
        "utterance_id": "u002"
      },
      "timestamps": {
        "start": "00:23.000",
        "end": "00:43.500",
        "confidence": "low"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "u004",
      "speaker": "mara-finch",
      "type": "interjection",
      "text": "Oof\u2014\u201clegible universe\u201d is SO it, but I\u2019m still stuck on the evidence part, because the show keeps letting lottery-proof function like prophecy without ever fully explaining why it\u2019s repeatably correct. Okay, what\u2019s our best candidate scene for \u201cinstruction\u201d the Numbers give\u2014Desmond\u2019s protocol moment, or something Locke gets wrong on purpose?",
      "delivery": {
        "emotion": "amused",
        "pace": "fast",
        "volume": "slightly_loud",
        "emphasis": [
          "legible-universe",
          "instruction-vs-evidence",
          "lottery-proof repeatably correct",
          "Desmond protocol",
          "Locke intentional misreading"
        ],
        "notes": "Make it quick and pointed; emphasize the need for a specific scene to anchor the Court."
      },
      "anchor": {
        "phrase": "stress-test that says \u201cyou will be accountable,\u201d not \u201cyou will be surprised.\u201d",
        "utterance_id": "u003"
      },
      "timestamps": {
        "start": "00:42.000",
        "end": "00:56.000",
        "confidence": "low"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "u005",
      "speaker": "mara-finch",
      "type": "speech",
      "text": "Yeah\u2014Desmond protocol is the best \u201cinstruction\u201d vibe because it\u2019s active coping, not passive mysticism: the Numbers aren\u2019t just right, they\u2019re used to *manage a person*. For evidence, though, lottery validation feels like the show basically winking \u201csee? fate exists,\u201d and that\u2019s where the mechanics holes start leaking. So in Plot Hole Court terms: do you think the Numbers are more like Dharma\u2019s system (human-built rules), or like Jacob\u2019s instrument (island-built consequences)?",
      "delivery": {
        "emotion": "warm",
        "pace": "slightly_slow",
        "volume": "normal",
        "emphasis": [
          "Desmond protocol as instruction",
          "lottery validation as evidence",
          "system vs instrument"
        ],
        "notes": "Set up Mara to choose a framing, then we can zoom into one specific scene next."
      },
      "anchor": {
        "phrase": "Desmond protocol is the best \u201cinstruction\u201d vibe",
        "utterance_id": "u004"
      },
      "timestamps": {
        "start": "00:55.000",
        "end": "01:15.000",
        "confidence": "low"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "u006",
      "speaker": "dev-navarro",
      "type": "speech",
      "text": "I think Dharma is the closest analog to the \u201csystem\u201d part, but Jacob/Smokey are what make it an \u201cinstrument\u201d\u2014because they\u2019re the ones who decide who gets the consequences and when, emotionally and socially. Dharma gives you rules; the island gives you meaning, even when the rules are identical on paper. If we\u2019re picking your Plot Hole Court framing for tomorrow: what would you say is the single moment where the Numbers feel like they\u2019re *administering consequences* rather than merely documenting them?",
      "delivery": {
        "emotion": "warm, skeptical",
        "pace": "slightly_slow",
        "volume": "normal",
